title: For Sale:  Spyderco C156GPBN Brad Southard Flipper
postcontent:
Selling due to unexpected bills, this knife has never been carried or used in any way. 
Like new. 100% condition. Serious buyers only, no lowballs, no trades. 
Must be 18+ to purchase.
Thank you.

$250 obo

MSRP: $419.99
length overall	7.96" (202 mm)	
blade length	3.46" (88 mm)	
blade steel	CTS 204P
length closed	4.50" (114 mm)	
cutting edge	3.46" (88 mm)	
weight	4.1 oz (11 g)
blade thickness	0.157" (4 mm)	
handle material	G-10 / Titanium

Brad Southard is an amazingly talented custom knifemaker who specializes in high-performance folder designs. His first collaboration with Spyderco features a "flipper"--a novel blade-opening device that was pioneered by custom knifemaker Kit Carson. A Carson Flipper consists of a small lever that extends from the base of the Southard's CTS 204P hollow-ground blade and protrudes from the back of the knife's handle when closed. Pulling on it with your index finger creates a tension against the detent mechanism that holds the blade closed. When the detent is overcome, the blade rotates on a special captive ball-bearing pivot system and snaps authoritatively into the open position.

The Southard's handle combines a textured Earth-brown G-10 scale and thick titanium liner on one side with a solid titanium scale on the other. The titanium scale forms the foundation of the knife's sturdy Reeve Integral Lock (R.I.L.) mechanism and features a small inlaid G-10 panel that acts as an overtravel stop when releasing the lock mechanism. It is also home to the knife's matching stainless steel clip, which supports right-side tip-up carry.

Offering an amazing synthesis of ergonomics, functionality, and state-of-the-art materials, the Southard is one of the most advanced Spyderco folders ever produced.

title: For Sale:  Winchester 1890 2nd Model Case Hardened Receiver
postcontent: Winchester Model 1890 slide-action rifle, take-down, 2nd Model with case-hardened receiver, caliber 22 Long. This rifle, with serial number 111400, was manufactured in 1901, the last year for the case-hardened receiver. The serial number only appears on the lower tang, which is correct for this rifle. It has a 24 inch octagon barrel. Although most of the case-hardening has worn off the receiver, there are still traces of it in protected areas, as around the take-down screw. The finish on the rest of the rifle is blue, fading to a brown patina. It has a good clean bore, with well-defined lands and grooves; although the bore is fairly bright, there appear to be some areas of very light roughness or pitting. The lettering is sharp and easily readable. The wood shows normal dings, dents, and scratches from use, but is not cracked or broken. The wood is proud to the metal and has a fair amount of original finish. There is one very small and old chip off the bottom of one of the rings on the slide handle. Although the front sight appears original, the rear sight was replaced with a King sight. One small screw on top the bolt is missing. The mechanics seem fine, but I have not fired this rifle. Returns only if not substantially as described and pictured. Must ship to an FFL or C&R (where legal). Ships within the U.S. only. Shipping cost will include insurance, at the buyer's expense.
